WEBVTT

00:06.756 --> 00:08.341
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:09.676 --> 00:10.552
(SCREAMING)

00:13.513 --> 00:15.557
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

00:16.474 --> 00:20.145
JEFF: <i>Monsters. We should be running</i>
<i>away from them, shouldn't we?</i>

00:20.603 --> 00:24.482
But so many of us, we run toward.

00:24.607 --> 00:25.817
(CHILDREN SCREAM)

00:26.026 --> 00:30.238
<i>Since I was a kid,</i>
<i>I've been into monsters.</i>

00:30.697 --> 00:32.532
MALE VOICE:<i> Godzilla,</i>
<i>king of the monsters.</i>

00:32.866 --> 00:33.992
(ROARS)

00:34.451 --> 00:37.162
JEFF:<i> They've been part of my psyche.</i>
<i>They wormed their way in.</i>

00:38.580 --> 00:43.543
Monsters, they have a great hold
on our imaginations. Why is that?

00:43.793 --> 00:45.170
(INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:45.295 --> 00:47.213
Everybody loves monsters.
I think it kind of

00:47.380 --> 00:48.882
<i>reminds us of our childhood.</i>

00:49.883 --> 00:51.885
I grew up on Frankenstein
and The Wolf Man.

00:52.010 --> 00:53.511
And then I can be that?

00:53.803 --> 00:55.263
(GROWLS)

00:55.513 --> 00:56.890
You know, I like that they're all unique.

00:59.267 --> 01:02.312
They have the sharp teeth
and their cool eyeballs.

01:03.021 --> 01:05.023
I don't like them, I love them.
Little bit more than like.

01:05.398 --> 01:07.233
If you love them so much,
why don't you marry them?

01:09.444 --> 01:11.237
-(FEMALE VOICE SCREAMING)
-(GROWLS)

01:11.404 --> 01:14.699
Everybody's crazy about monsters.

01:14.908 --> 01:18.244
Why? Why? Good question.

01:31.049 --> 01:34.135
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

01:34.594 --> 01:38.056
What's the most popular movie
that I was in, where I was a monster?

01:39.682 --> 01:41.392
JEFF: (IMITATES BUZZING) <i>The Fly.</i>

01:42.352 --> 01:44.979
<i>Hey, there's, Stephan Dupuis</i>
<i>applying prosthetics.</i>

01:45.980 --> 01:48.483
<i>And it was five hours</i>
<i>in that makeup chair.</i>

01:50.276 --> 01:52.862
<i>But here,</i>
<i>shopping at this monster mega-store,</i>

01:53.154 --> 01:54.614
<i>it takes just a few seconds.</i>

01:55.949 --> 01:58.535
<i>Emporiums, like this one,</i>
<i>are around because so many of us</i>

01:58.618 --> 02:01.204
<i>seemed to be just</i>
<i>fascinated with monsters.</i>

02:01.704 --> 02:02.747
(CROWD CHEERS)

02:02.831 --> 02:06.209
JEFF:<i> Every Halloween, Americans spend</i>
<i>around eight billion bucks.</i>

02:06.543 --> 02:08.920
<i>'Cause I guess dressing up</i>
<i>like our favorite monster</i>

02:09.212 --> 02:10.588
<i>is just getting more and more popular.</i>

02:11.381 --> 02:13.967
So you make these things, you're
the expert, I have a billion questions.

02:14.300 --> 02:19.139
But let me ask you this.
What elements makes a monster mask scary?

02:19.639 --> 02:22.851
I think, maybe the first thing is,
maybe studying

02:23.059 --> 02:26.104
human and animal anatomy,
you know, the realism

02:26.187 --> 02:29.065
of wrinkle patterns and 45-degree angles.

02:29.315 --> 02:31.526
You know, when I look angry,
you know, my face kind of creates

02:31.693 --> 02:33.069
these certain angles.

02:33.153 --> 02:35.655
And we can kind of see it
on maybe some of these masks here.

02:35.822 --> 02:38.158
You know, this mask,
it's got a baked-in expression

02:38.283 --> 02:41.870
that kind of automatically reads,
you know, fearsome and intense.

02:41.995 --> 02:42.996
Yes.

02:46.875 --> 02:50.420
ANDREW: This is kind of our take
on a classic character, we call him Frank.

02:50.587 --> 02:52.714
Now, is it all done? It is all finished?

02:52.881 --> 02:56.217
We do offer customization.
Maybe you'd like to try it on?

02:56.509 --> 03:00.054
Yes, yes. Oh, my God, okay.

03:01.431 --> 03:03.308
Oh, there we go, look at it, it's alive.

03:03.892 --> 03:05.059
JEFF: It's alive.

03:05.685 --> 03:10.481
I love it.
But maybe it should be greenish.

03:10.565 --> 03:12.483
ANDREW: We could do that, yeah,
we can customize this.

03:12.567 --> 03:13.860
-JEFF: Really? Okay.
-ANDREW: Yeah. Yeah.

03:13.985 --> 03:15.111
JEFF: All right, thank you so much.

03:15.236 --> 03:17.822
Awesome, and I hope it doesn't scare
your kids too much.

03:19.532 --> 03:22.827
JEFF: <i>Although these disguises</i>
<i>are ghoulish and grotesque,</i>

03:23.203 --> 03:26.289
<i>I think that they're just fun</i>
<i>with fantasia.</i>

03:27.040 --> 03:31.878
But is there something monstrous
out there in the real world

03:32.086 --> 03:34.797
<i>that serves as the terrifying</i>

03:35.048 --> 03:38.593
<i>-inspiration behind these masks?</i>
-(GROWLING)

03:40.970 --> 03:42.013
What do you think?

03:42.263 --> 03:45.975
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

03:48.353 --> 03:51.356
(DRAMATIC MUSIC CONCLUDES)

03:51.773 --> 03:56.069
Let's get deep, deep into these woods.

03:56.861 --> 03:58.071
<i>Hmm...</i>

03:58.196 --> 04:03.409
The woods are full of poetry
and beauty, and loveliness,

04:03.493 --> 04:06.329
but also dark, powerful forces.

04:07.705 --> 04:11.709
<i>Here's the question,</i>
<i>what could be lurking out in the woods?</i>

04:12.961 --> 04:15.797
I'm ready for it. Are you?

04:24.931 --> 04:30.103
(DANA IMITATING LOVEBIRD CALL)

04:38.319 --> 04:42.657
<i>Meet Mr. and Mrs. Newkirk.</i>
<i>These lovebird's calls...</i>

04:42.740 --> 04:44.575
-(IMITATES LOVEBIRD CALLS)
-JEFF: <i>...are an attempt to attract</i>

04:44.701 --> 04:47.453
<i>one of the world's most elusive monsters.</i>

04:47.829 --> 04:48.788
(SCREAMING)

04:48.913 --> 04:51.708
NEWS ANCHOR: <i>The primitive</i>
<i>man-like creature, very similar...</i>

04:51.833 --> 04:53.876
to the Yeti or the Himalayan Snowman.

04:54.085 --> 04:55.878
It's the footprint evidence
that's convinced me

04:55.962 --> 04:58.006
-that there's something out there.
-Hence, Bigfoot.

05:00.800 --> 05:02.510
They're the reason we actually
believe in Bigfoot.

05:02.760 --> 05:04.512
These guys that
took us out Bigfoot hunting.

05:04.595 --> 05:06.347
They taught us how to some Bigfoot calls.

05:07.181 --> 05:08.433
And then something,

05:08.641 --> 05:11.477
yelled back at us
and there was just no way

05:11.602 --> 05:14.522
-it could have been a person.
-To be able to fill their lungs up,

05:14.814 --> 05:17.025
with that much power, it was unbelievable.

05:17.483 --> 05:19.861
-Do you want to try one?
-Well, I don't know I'm... (CHUCKLES)

05:19.944 --> 05:23.323
-...of poor... Yes, I... Okay.
-(ALL CHUCKLE)

05:23.656 --> 05:26.534
Okay, we're going to see
something running towards us,

05:26.659 --> 05:29.120
as soon as I do this
and what are you going to do then,

05:29.203 --> 05:30.496
-if that happens? Do we have...
-Photographs.

05:30.580 --> 05:31.914
-Take pictures.
-Take pictures?

05:31.998 --> 05:33.291
-Of course.
-Okay

05:33.541 --> 05:38.129
(IMITATING LOVEBIRD CALL)

05:38.212 --> 05:39.047
Bigfoot!

05:45.261 --> 05:46.596
Bigfoot? Big!

05:47.263 --> 05:49.390
-(GROWLS)
-(OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING)

05:52.477 --> 05:54.771
Oh, my God! I just saw something.

05:57.398 --> 05:59.734
I thought that was exactly
the distance from which...

05:59.859 --> 06:01.194
It was one of our crew members.

06:02.487 --> 06:04.364
-GREG: Kind of walking like Bigfoot
-JEFF: I really thought...

06:04.530 --> 06:06.240
I really thought it was,
look at that, there he is.

06:06.324 --> 06:07.492
-(CHUCKLES)
-JEFF: Oh, no.

06:09.202 --> 06:13.122
<i>Well, I think they can tell that</i>
<i>I'm not so convinced that Bigfoot exists.</i>

06:13.206 --> 06:16.667
<i>But plenty of folks really are.</i>
<i>And, you know, they go on</i>

06:16.751 --> 06:21.255
<i>these so-called hunts for Bigfoot,</i>
<i>all across the Pacific coastal region.</i>

06:21.464 --> 06:24.509
<i>They lay bait, release a mixture</i>

06:24.592 --> 06:26.886
<i>of pheromones from humans and apes.</i>

06:27.470 --> 06:30.640
That's horrible. (GROANS, COUGHS)

06:30.807 --> 06:33.810
<i>And they recreate</i>
<i>the strange knocking sounds</i>

06:33.893 --> 06:36.229
<i>that have reportedly come from Bigfoot.</i>

06:37.271 --> 06:40.608
<i>Some people even claim</i>
<i>to have actual evidence.</i>

06:42.360 --> 06:47.281
Jeff, we run a traveling museum
of paranormal and occult artifacts,

06:47.865 --> 06:51.202
and a big part of our collection
are Bigfoot casts.

06:51.536 --> 06:53.037
This is the cast that started it all.

06:53.746 --> 06:55.748
-This is?
-This is from Bluff Creek.

06:56.040 --> 06:58.042
JEFF: This is the first Bigfoot print
I've ever seen in my life.

06:58.167 --> 07:00.086
-GREG: You've never seen one up close?
-Are you kidding? No! Never.

07:00.420 --> 07:01.587
GREG: That's a Yeti print.

07:02.296 --> 07:05.007
It probably could cruise through
the snow a lot easier than this one.

07:05.133 --> 07:06.134
-"Cruise"?
-Yeah.

07:06.259 --> 07:07.260
-You say, "Cruise"?
-DANA: Yeah.

07:07.343 --> 07:08.719
Do you know how tall Tom Cruise

07:08.845 --> 07:11.055
-is actually in real life?
-Mm-hmm.

07:11.180 --> 07:14.308
-He's like a Keebler elf, tiny, tiny.
-(DANA CHUCKLES)

07:14.684 --> 07:16.018
-Tiny, like a little...
-DANA: I love it

07:16.102 --> 07:16.978
...little cracker. Yeah.

07:17.228 --> 07:20.773
-Oh, what's this? This is a baby foot.
-This is from...

07:21.482 --> 07:24.318
what's called locally the Orang Pendek.

07:24.444 --> 07:27.029
The farmers in Indonesia,
keep seeing, what they say,

07:27.155 --> 07:29.866
"A little man
who looks very primate-like."

07:30.324 --> 07:32.493
-Tom Cruise.
-Maybe.

07:32.577 --> 07:33.494
(ALL CHUCKLE)

07:34.203 --> 07:38.666
So there are animals out there,
that we maybe won't discover

07:38.875 --> 07:40.960
for tens if not hundreds of years.

07:42.295 --> 07:46.924
JEFF: <i>The Newkirkâ€™s are convinced,</i>
<i>not only about the existence of Bigfoot,</i>

07:47.175 --> 07:50.595
<i>but that there are countless other</i>
<i>undiscovered monsters</i>

07:50.678 --> 07:51.888
<i>all around the world.</i>

07:53.097 --> 07:54.432
<i>From the Loch Ness Monster...</i>

07:54.974 --> 07:56.976
<i>We shot the head and the four humps.</i>

07:57.477 --> 07:58.978
JEFF: <i>...to the Himalayan Yeti.</i>

07:59.645 --> 08:02.607
<i>Could it be the power of storytelling</i>

08:02.732 --> 08:04.442
<i>that keep monsters alive?</i>

08:05.193 --> 08:08.654
<i>Tales told by the flickering light</i>
<i>of the evocative campfire.</i>

08:09.947 --> 08:11.365
-You're a folklorist, but how do...
-DR. LYNNE: I know.

08:11.449 --> 08:12.575
-Let me ask you this.
-DR. LYNNE: Yes.

08:12.658 --> 08:15.703
JEFF: Why specifically,
is the Bigfoot legend...

08:15.786 --> 08:17.663
Why is that relevant?
Why does it continue?

08:17.788 --> 08:20.625
-Why are we interested in that?
-I think Bigfoot gives us a way

08:20.791 --> 08:24.253
to speak symbolically about the value
of the natural environment.

08:24.629 --> 08:31.219
Just the idea, that a large
bipedal hairy hominid could exist.

08:31.469 --> 08:32.929
-Undiscovered...
-JEFF: Yeah.

08:33.137 --> 08:34.847
...in our country...

08:35.097 --> 08:38.601
-JEFF: Yes, yeah.
-...means we haven't totally ruined it.

08:39.060 --> 08:40.728
Right, right, right.

08:40.811 --> 08:45.358
Really, when we think about how popular
Bigfoot has become, it is a sense

08:45.441 --> 08:48.402
that maybe we are
even on an unconscious level,

08:48.486 --> 08:52.114
hyper-focused on protecting
the natural world around us.

08:52.323 --> 08:53.908
GREG: But there's also
that mystery too, right?

08:53.991 --> 08:55.701
-Mm-hmm.
-GREG: We like to go out into the forest

08:55.785 --> 08:57.036
-and look for things...
-DR. LYNNE: Yeah.

08:57.119 --> 08:58.538
...that may very well not exist.

08:58.871 --> 09:00.581
We're not so interested in convincing

09:00.665 --> 09:01.874
-anyone of anything.
-DR. LYNNE: Yeah.

09:02.166 --> 09:05.211
We're most interested
in preserving elements of those stories.

09:05.503 --> 09:08.464
Because we can learn a lot
from our monsters.

09:08.965 --> 09:11.384
JEFF: <i>Ooh, ooh.</i>
<i>I like what I'm hearing now,</i>

09:11.634 --> 09:14.971
<i>that monsters are trying to tell us</i>
<i>something important.</i>

09:16.889 --> 09:21.143
<i>I mean, the very word monster</i>
<i>comes from the Latin verb, </i>monere.

09:21.686 --> 09:24.689
<i>Which means to show or to forewarn.</i>

09:25.898 --> 09:28.859
<i>Childhood yarns, about the things</i>
<i>like the big bad wolf,</i>

09:29.318 --> 09:33.406
<i>can be interpreted as warnings</i>
<i>to stay safe.</i>

09:34.574 --> 09:38.160
<i>Some were most validly realized monsters</i>
<i>are of the product</i>

09:38.244 --> 09:39.620
<i>of the collective fears</i>

09:39.912 --> 09:42.582
<i>that grip the times</i>
<i>in which they were created.</i>

09:44.166 --> 09:47.712
<i>For instance, this poor guy,</i>
<i>he sprang to life in the 19th century</i>

09:47.795 --> 09:52.550
<i>when electrifying scientific</i>
<i>experimentation struck fear</i>

09:52.717 --> 09:54.760
<i>into our vulnerable hearts.</i>

09:55.344 --> 09:58.764
<i>Blast forward to an irradiated Japan</i>
<i>in the 1950s,</i>

09:59.056 --> 10:01.267
<i>and you'll get a giant mutant lizard.</i>

10:01.601 --> 10:03.853
(ROARS)

10:03.936 --> 10:06.397
<i>And it doesn't take a wild leap</i>
<i>of analysis to see</i>

10:06.480 --> 10:10.067
<i>how the unnerving promise of exploring</i>
<i>our solar system,</i>

10:10.234 --> 10:15.281
<i>in the swingin' and turbulent '60s,</i>
<i>led to a certain alien anxiety.</i>

10:16.782 --> 10:19.243
MALE VOICE:<i> Adventure,</i>
<i>we'll make you wonder if it's true,</i>

10:19.577 --> 10:21.829
<i>while your eyes convince you that it is.</i>

10:23.205 --> 10:27.501
JEFF: <i>For the better part of a century,</i>
<i>Hollywood has been a major part</i>

10:28.002 --> 10:31.213
<i>of giving a face and form to our monsters.</i>

10:31.380 --> 10:32.381
(SCREAMS)

10:32.548 --> 10:37.094
JEFF:<i> And one man, in particular</i>
<i>has delved deeply.</i>

10:37.803 --> 10:39.555
There's so much to see here.

10:42.224 --> 10:46.520
<i>Phil Tippett and I, first met on the set</i>
<i>of a little picture called </i>Jurassic Park

10:46.854 --> 10:48.356
<i>almost 30 years ago.</i>

10:49.565 --> 10:51.567
<i>He's a master monster maker.</i>

10:51.692 --> 10:54.320
<i>A Hollywood legend,</i>
<i>he's got two Academy Awards.</i>

10:55.154 --> 10:57.907
<i>He works with the mysteries</i>
<i>of the subconscious,</i>

10:58.616 --> 11:01.577
<i>and brilliantly brings to life</i>

11:01.827 --> 11:03.537
<i>some of our worst nightmares.</i>

11:04.664 --> 11:06.707
-Hello, Phil Tippett.
-What are you doing here?

11:07.667 --> 11:08.834
(JEFF CHUCKLING)

11:09.085 --> 11:10.836
He's crochety, "What are you doing here?"

11:11.003 --> 11:12.046
It's been a while.

11:12.338 --> 11:15.800
Well, that's what I want to talk
to you about, monsters.

11:16.258 --> 11:18.302
We're talking about monsters
in this thing.

11:18.761 --> 11:19.845
You're a great artist.

11:20.221 --> 11:23.391
And your subject matter is...
it's monsters.

11:23.474 --> 11:26.977
Personally, I think monsters come
from a lot of different directions.

11:27.978 --> 11:33.109
Some are historical. You know, dragons,
dragon's a good example of,

11:33.275 --> 11:37.655
like, kind of a metaphor
for forces of nature and wind,

11:37.822 --> 11:42.201
and lightning, and others
are internal and psychological.

11:42.368 --> 11:45.746
<i>And so, usually,</i>
<i>what I try and do with making a monster is</i>

11:45.871 --> 11:47.957
<i>I just try and put</i>
<i>everything out of my mind,</i>

11:48.124 --> 11:51.043
and just let it sit until a concept

11:51.627 --> 11:53.254
pops into my head out of nowhere.

11:53.379 --> 11:55.881
Then I just sit down with the clay
and it's just like...

11:56.006 --> 11:57.091
(MUMBLES, SIGHS)

11:57.258 --> 11:58.342
-Really?
-PHIL: Yeah.

11:58.551 --> 11:59.760
That's so interesting.

12:00.094 --> 12:02.054
So that's my brain. Let's get into yours.

12:02.221 --> 12:03.723
Okay. (HISSES)

12:05.808 --> 12:11.313
So this is the mold room.
This is where we do a lot of casting,

12:12.314 --> 12:15.151
<i>sculpting, and painting.</i>

12:15.276 --> 12:17.862
JEFF:<i> Amazing. Amazing. Amazing. Wow.</i>

12:19.655 --> 12:23.743
-PHIL: What do you say we make a monster?
-I'd like to make a monster.

12:23.993 --> 12:27.037
There's a million ways to make a monster.

12:27.163 --> 12:30.833
And each one is, like,
I think kind of personal.

12:31.208 --> 12:33.419
What I thought we could orbit was...

12:34.712 --> 12:36.922
something kind of deep.

12:37.631 --> 12:38.924
How do you feel about your mother?

12:42.720 --> 12:47.057
You know, I had many different feelings
about my mother, but Shirley Goldblum,

12:47.349 --> 12:50.478
<i>who died at age 85, some years ago.</i>

12:51.687 --> 12:56.358
<i>Well, she was a very nurturing in a way.</i>
<i>But also, she had the gift of fury.</i>

12:56.734 --> 13:00.321
And, Mommy was, yes, a figure of fear.

13:00.946 --> 13:03.365
Well, what I would propose is that

13:04.283 --> 13:07.661
we each make a three-dimensional effigy

13:08.537 --> 13:13.250
of the mental picture
of the mother monster.

13:13.334 --> 13:15.461
-Wow.
-You create your monster.

13:15.628 --> 13:17.505
-I'll create my monster.
-Excellent.

13:18.380 --> 13:22.343
(GROWLS)

13:22.843 --> 13:25.262
<i>Now, my mom was not literally a monster...</i>

13:25.387 --> 13:27.598
She was dark around here.

13:27.723 --> 13:30.351
<i>...but Phil is digging</i>
<i>into something here that's deeper.</i>

13:30.768 --> 13:32.228
<i>The archetype maternal</i>

13:32.603 --> 13:35.606
<i>is traditionally romanticized</i>
<i>as nurturing,</i>

13:35.731 --> 13:38.984
<i>but it can also represent</i>
<i>our first taste of authority.</i>

13:39.235 --> 13:43.280
<i>So, naturally, it can inspire</i>
<i>not only love, but also fear.</i>

13:43.656 --> 13:44.990
Look at that, yeah.

13:46.116 --> 13:48.536
Okay. That's horrible.

13:49.036 --> 13:50.996
Horrible. Horrible.

13:52.081 --> 13:54.458
<i>Hey, forget about the fangs and the fur.</i>

13:54.667 --> 13:55.835
<i>When it comes to monsters,</i>

13:55.960 --> 13:58.963
<i>it's what's going on</i>
<i>on the inside that counts.</i>

13:59.630 --> 14:04.260
<i>In the cocktail shaker of our inner lives,</i>
<i>almost anything can become</i>

14:04.468 --> 14:07.179
<i>-monstrously mangled and shocking.</i>
-(SCREAMS)

14:07.263 --> 14:08.264
(GROWLING)

14:08.430 --> 14:11.016
<i>Well, what was it? Out with it, kid.</i>

14:11.517 --> 14:14.019
<i>Well, it's kind of like a...</i>
<i>it's kind of like a mass</i>

14:14.103 --> 14:16.146
<i>that just keeps getting</i>
<i>bigger and bigger, it...</i>

14:22.570 --> 14:26.490
JEFF: <i>Yeah, Steve, even oozing,</i>
<i>runaway raspberry Jell-O</i>

14:27.032 --> 14:28.617
<i>can morph into a vehicle...</i>

14:29.034 --> 14:31.704
<i>...for our long-buried terrors.</i>

14:32.204 --> 14:35.040
<i>And the monsters that emerge,</i>
<i>a precious glimpse inside</i>

14:35.124 --> 14:37.376
<i>your murky subconscious.</i>

14:37.877 --> 14:39.211
Yours looks very good.

14:39.378 --> 14:41.046
And what if you did something with that.

14:41.213 --> 14:44.008
As I've made a very good start.
A very good start.

14:45.426 --> 14:46.719
<i>Okay, well, not really.</i>

14:47.428 --> 14:49.221
<i>I didn't get too much done.</i>
<i>So, over to you, maestro.</i>

14:49.805 --> 14:53.017
(UPBEAT MUSIC CONCLUDES)

14:54.018 --> 14:55.477
Hey, that's fantastic.

14:56.145 --> 14:59.064
Look at that. Really... Oh, wait a minute.

15:00.149 --> 15:02.818
You did get her, look at that.

15:08.032 --> 15:09.950
Oh! Oh! Here we go.

15:10.075 --> 15:11.952
-One hour later...
-JEFF: Yes.

15:12.036 --> 15:14.788
-...we take the buns out of the oven.
-JEFF: Okay.

15:15.497 --> 15:18.125
Mm, hmm, hmm. Something's cooking.

15:18.292 --> 15:19.627
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

15:20.169 --> 15:24.506
(GROWLS)

15:24.965 --> 15:26.675
Monsters, the monsters...

15:27.968 --> 15:29.929
live inside your memories.

15:30.012 --> 15:33.974
Some that you'll never forget.
And I myself, sitting at the feet

15:34.058 --> 15:35.976
of the great one... A Tippett

15:36.268 --> 15:40.564
<i>I've delved into my own storehouse</i>
<i>of scares and fear.</i>

15:40.898 --> 15:43.317
<i>Now that he has, gently but firmly,</i>

15:43.609 --> 15:46.153
loosened the top on the pickle jar,

15:46.987 --> 15:50.199
I might be ready to open that jar.

15:50.741 --> 15:53.786
Smell that brine, just thrust our hand,

15:54.119 --> 15:58.082
pull out a good,
juicy, garlicky pickle of fear...

15:59.333 --> 16:00.376
and...

16:01.835 --> 16:03.504
go further, take a bite.

16:04.296 --> 16:06.632
(GROWLS)

16:09.134 --> 16:11.053
JEFF: <i>Dearest tender viewer,</i>

16:11.470 --> 16:14.390
<i>if the word monster</i>
<i>means anything at all,</i>

16:14.515 --> 16:16.809
<i>then it certainly must point to</i>

16:17.309 --> 16:19.311
<i>what scares you the most.</i>

16:20.104 --> 16:21.105
(GROANS)

16:21.188 --> 16:22.940
<i>And at the end of every scary movie,</i>

16:23.232 --> 16:25.776
<i>the hero must face the monster.</i>

16:26.151 --> 16:30.114
<i>His gherkin of dread,</i>
<i>his cornichon of horror.</i>

16:32.116 --> 16:33.158
(GASPS, CHUCKLES)

16:33.242 --> 16:36.078
-Hi.
-JEFF: I'm... You scared me already.

16:37.621 --> 16:39.873
<i>So, then why do we love</i>
<i>a good fright so much?</i>

16:40.666 --> 16:44.712
<i>Well, in order to find out,</i>
<i>I've agreed to be part of an experiment</i>

16:45.087 --> 16:49.508
<i>in the terrors that can be found</i>
<i>at LA's Midnight Mortuary.</i>

16:50.050 --> 16:53.387
-Wow, is this a spooky security?
-Oh, don't look at it too much.

16:53.762 --> 16:56.348
Oh? Don't look at that yet, yet.
Oh, I want to be surprised.

16:56.974 --> 17:00.436
<i>Okay, before the fun begins,</i>
<i>I'm getting wired up here</i>

17:00.561 --> 17:02.187
<i>with my vitals tracked.</i>

17:02.855 --> 17:05.274
<i>As I'm probably going to get</i>
<i>the life scared out of me,</i>

17:05.482 --> 17:09.236
<i>in order to finally understand, I guess,</i>
<i>why we embrace monsters.</i>

17:10.029 --> 17:11.071
Come on in, welcome...

17:11.321 --> 17:13.073
-Thank you.
-...to the Midnight Mortuary.

17:13.157 --> 17:18.787
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

17:28.422 --> 17:29.548
-(SCREAMS)
-(JEFF WHIMPERING)

17:42.311 --> 17:44.229
-(SCREAMS)
-JEFF: Whoa.

17:45.147 --> 17:49.068
-(SCREAMS)
-Wow! Jeez! Jeez! Oh.

17:51.361 --> 17:53.697
Oh, yeah! Don't do that.

17:59.703 --> 18:01.371
-(ELECTRICITY BUZZING)
-JEFF: Oh, golly!

18:04.374 --> 18:07.419
-Okay, oh, hey, hey, hey!
-(GROWLS)

18:08.378 --> 18:09.797
-(MONSTER SCREAMS)
-Whoa, whoa.

18:11.381 --> 18:12.716
-(GROWLS)
-Whoa.

18:12.883 --> 18:14.384
Let me out! Let me out!

18:16.136 --> 18:19.473
-You made it! (CHUCKLES)
-Oh, oh, wow.

18:19.848 --> 18:23.018
How you feeling? Is your heart beating?

18:23.185 --> 18:24.478
-JEFF: Yeah.
-Yeah? What did you think?

18:24.561 --> 18:25.854
Are you fe... Was it scary?

18:26.063 --> 18:27.314
-JEFF: Yeah, it was.
-Yeah?

18:27.523 --> 18:29.358
-Yeah, it was great.
-AMY: Good. But you had fun?

18:29.525 --> 18:31.026
-Yeah, it was fun..
-AMY: Good.

18:31.151 --> 18:34.571
-And really scary.
-Let's go get your data checked out.

18:34.696 --> 18:36.490
Okay, let's go check my vitals.

18:38.158 --> 18:40.828
-Hmm, let's see, this is me?
-DR. MARGEE: Okay, so

18:40.953 --> 18:43.497
this is you. This is what we're looking
at right now, are changes

18:43.622 --> 18:45.415
in your skin conductance over time.

18:45.749 --> 18:47.793
-Really?
-This area here is where you were

18:47.918 --> 18:49.795
kind of hanging out
in the morgue for a little bit.

18:50.003 --> 18:51.964
-That was spooky... (SHUDDERS)
-DR. MARGEE: Yeah, I know.

18:52.047 --> 18:54.591
-Horrible. Horrible.
-DR. MARGEE: On your data,

18:54.716 --> 18:59.263
a lot of the activity we see
is any anticipation of the threats.

18:59.388 --> 19:02.808
You don't know what you are about to face
and so your body is saying,

19:02.891 --> 19:06.645
"I'd better just give it all we got.
We have to be prepared."

19:07.813 --> 19:10.065
So that's a great thing to see
that reactivity,

19:10.315 --> 19:11.483
responsiveness in the moment.

19:11.775 --> 19:14.820
Oh, my gosh, I'm an easy and happy,

19:15.070 --> 19:16.655
delighted jumper.

19:16.822 --> 19:18.740
-DR. MARGEE: Yeah, well...
-I like to get...

19:19.158 --> 19:21.201
I mean, I don't like it,
but I like it, you know?

19:21.326 --> 19:24.246
We're doing something that is stressful,
that is challenging,

19:24.329 --> 19:27.416
that has elements of it
that are actually uncomfortable,

19:27.499 --> 19:28.584
that you don't like.

19:28.667 --> 19:30.002
-Yeah.
-DR. MARGEE: But you keep going,

19:30.127 --> 19:31.628
and so we've evolved

19:31.712 --> 19:33.964
to be really happy
when we do something stressful

19:34.089 --> 19:36.258
and we make it out the other side
and we're still here.

19:36.341 --> 19:37.259
(INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

19:37.384 --> 19:41.013
JEFF: <i>Fear and fun, man and monster,</i>
<i>it's such a complicated relationship</i>

19:41.096 --> 19:44.433
<i>that's both, I think,</i>
<i>physical and psychological.</i>

19:44.892 --> 19:48.228
<i>Let's explore, the brain,</i>
<i>when gripped by terror,</i>

19:48.353 --> 19:51.190
<i>unleashes a surge of chemicals</i>
<i>to prepare the body</i>

19:51.398 --> 19:53.317
<i>for that famous fight or flight.</i>

19:53.734 --> 19:56.820
<i>One of those chemicals</i>
<i>it's something called noradrenaline,</i>

19:57.237 --> 20:00.407
<i>it tears through the body,</i>
<i>and causes dry mouth</i>

20:00.699 --> 20:02.868
<i>and those butterflies in the stomach.</i>

20:03.410 --> 20:07.539
<i>But you know what,</i>
<i>noradrenaline also gets released</i>

20:07.664 --> 20:10.417
<i>when we experience</i>
<i>that thing called falling in love.</i>

20:11.084 --> 20:15.297
<i>Hey, that might explain a thing or two,</i>
<i>and here's another chemical,</i>

20:15.422 --> 20:17.883
<i>this is, oxytocin.</i>
<i>You might be familiar with that.</i>

20:18.050 --> 20:21.345
<i>And it gets released too,</i>
<i>when you're frightened, to calm you down.</i>

20:21.553 --> 20:26.808
<i>But it also is there</i>
<i>for the bonding with other people,</i>

20:26.975 --> 20:29.603
<i>toward whom you might feel</i>
<i>particularly affectionate.</i>

20:29.895 --> 20:34.524
<i>Isn't that something?</i>
<i>So it's this powerful chemical response...</i>

20:34.691 --> 20:36.401
-(MONSTER CHUCKLING)
<i>-...that blurs the boundaries</i>

20:36.485 --> 20:38.612
<i>between love and fear</i>

20:38.695 --> 20:41.865
<i>that makes monsters</i>
<i>so difficult to resist.</i>

20:42.658 --> 20:44.076
(FEMALE VOICE CHUCKLING)

20:44.368 --> 20:45.869
JEFF:<i> Well, that's enough</i>
<i>of me getting scared,</i>

20:45.953 --> 20:47.704
<i>hey, how about I turn the tables</i>

20:47.996 --> 20:51.708
<i>and try to scare</i>
<i>the bejesus out of some other people?</i>

20:52.292 --> 20:54.795
-(WHIRRING)
-Okey dokey.

20:54.962 --> 20:57.464
-(WHIRRING)
-MALE VOICE 1: That doesn't look too good.

20:59.007 --> 21:00.008
MALE VOICE 2: Here we go.

21:00.175 --> 21:02.094
-(WHIMPERING)
-(WOMAN SCREAMING)

21:02.552 --> 21:04.805
-(ALL SCREAM)
-Oh, my God!

21:05.222 --> 21:07.599
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

21:07.766 --> 21:08.850
MALE VOICE: Oh!

21:11.645 --> 21:13.105
-FEMALE VOICE 1: I don't like it.
-FEMALE VOICE 2: Okay.

21:13.188 --> 21:14.064
(ALL SCREAM)

21:14.273 --> 21:17.192
JEFF: <i>What seemed so illogical,</i>
<i>now kind of makes sense.</i>

21:17.818 --> 21:21.446
<i>Getting scared by a monster</i>
<i>can be a stone gas.</i>

21:22.030 --> 21:23.156
-(SCREAMS)
-(SCREAMS)

21:23.365 --> 21:25.617
JEFF:<i> It makes us huddle close,</i>
<i>tight together,</i>

21:26.243 --> 21:30.789
<i>and feel so connected to each other.</i>
<i>And as long as we survive,</i>

21:30.956 --> 21:35.002
<i>that moment of sheer panic</i>
<i>can give way to a sublime</i>

21:35.127 --> 21:37.546
<i>intoxication and ecstasy.</i>

21:38.380 --> 21:42.426
<i>We can find infinite joy</i>
<i>in that bonding experience</i>

21:42.509 --> 21:45.929
<i>of running through a haunted house,</i>
<i>or packing ourselves</i>

21:46.013 --> 21:49.141
<i>into the bosom of a glorious theater.</i>

21:49.766 --> 21:51.768
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

21:54.396 --> 22:01.153
(MELANCHOLIC MUSIC PLAYING)

22:04.573 --> 22:07.617
JEFF: Let's see, I have a feeling
I know who this is from.

22:08.869 --> 22:12.414
Remember the question
that I asked at the beginning?

22:12.497 --> 22:16.376
"Why is it that so-called monsters
have a hold on us?"

22:16.710 --> 22:20.714
Well, we may have discovered that monsters

22:21.048 --> 22:24.468
help us make sense of a scary world.
What do you think about that?

22:24.676 --> 22:27.554
<i>And maybe they make us</i>
<i>stronger and braver.</i>

22:28.555 --> 22:31.350
Maybe there's a monster in all of us.

22:31.975 --> 22:33.602
I think there may be.

22:34.770 --> 22:36.271
Wow. Wait a minute.

22:44.863 --> 22:45.989
Don't be afraid.

22:47.074 --> 22:49.993
Don't be afraid of being afraid.

22:50.744 --> 22:52.245
Embrace your monster.

22:57.793 --> 22:59.961
-(GROWLING)
-(FEMALE VOICE SCREAMING)

23:00.462 --> 23:01.588
(CHILD CHUCKLING)

23:01.797 --> 23:08.470
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

